{"user": "I heard about calculating effect sizes in educational studies. Could you explain how that works?", "assistant": "Certainly! Effect size (ES) is a way of quantifying the difference between two groups. In educational research, it often involves comparing the mean score of a control group with a treatment group at the posttest stage. The formula used is:

ES ≈ (Mean of Treatment Group - Mean of Control Group) / Pooled Standard Deviation. 

If a pretest was conducted, we adjust for initial differences by considering pretest scores as well."}
